\b0\fs24 Khigga is a style of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assyrian_folk_dance"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Assyrian folk dance}} in which multiple dancers hold each other's hands and form a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle_dance"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 circle}}. There are multiple foot patterns that dancers perform. Its thought to have been danced for thousands of years. It is usually performed at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weddings"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 weddings}} and other joyous occasions.\
\
Khigga is traditionally danced with music played on the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zurna"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 zurna}}, supported by a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Davul"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 davul}}, but in recent years, electronic instruments have started to replace them.\cf2 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 The khigga has spread from Anatolia to many other regions, such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armenia"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 Armenia}} and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balkans"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 Balkans}}. The khigga is a group of traditional hand-holding {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dance"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 dances}} similar to those from the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balkans"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 Balkans}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eastern_European"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 Eastern European}} countries, with a single or a couple of figure dancers often added to the geometrical centre of the dancing circle.\cf2 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 In Assyrian weddings, as well as parties and other various social gatherings, people may dance khigga for hours. Every region has its own style and forms. Khigga is simple to dance and it is the first beat that is played in welcoming the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bride"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 bride}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Groom"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 groom}} to the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wedding_reception"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 reception}} hall.\
