\cf2 \cb3 As with most Assyrian folk dances, khigga assumes an open circular shape. In a restricted floor space (e.g. a lot of tables), the dance tend to wind over the room and assume {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spiral"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 spiral}}, circular and curvy shapes.\cf2 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 Arms are predominantly used which usually move independently of the legs. Arm motions include bouncing, swinging forward and back, moving side-to-side. The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Torso"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 torso}}, along with the shoulders and arms, bounces up and down rhythmically, often independently of the legs. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stomp_(strike)"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 Stomps}} and stamps are also present.\cf2 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 Khigga has other sub-styles such as "Heavy Khigga" or "Normal Khigga". Heavy simply means the same dance beat but slower. Khigga goes by the time signature of 4/4 and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tempo"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb3 tempo}} between 100 and 115.\cf2 \cb1 \
